the government has resigned under pressure 
from labor unions and the military over its failure to end sudans 
civil war 
newspapers said sunday the outgoing cabinets junior partner the 
fundamentalist national islamic front is expected to stay out of 
the next government because of its objection to a proposal to freeze 
islamic law 
prime minister sadek mahdi handed his cabinets resignation late 
saturday to the state council the countrys collective presidency 
ten days earlier mahdi and 65 heads of political parties and 
unions signed a plan calling for a new government 
the army unions and opposition political groups had issued an 
ultimatum to form a broadbased government and start peace talks 
with the rebel sudan peoples liberation army in the south 
there was no word sunday on when a new government will be named 
the capital of khartoum tense since the armys ultimatum three 
weeks ago was quiet however helmeted riot police with shields and 
batons stood guard on curbs and street corners 
the independent daily newspaper alkhartoum said mahdis new 
government will include eight seats for his umma party five for the 
centrist democratic unionist party and two for the powerful trade 
unions and professional associations 
it would be the first time the unions and associations have 
shared power since a member of a doctors group headed a 
transitional cabinet for a year after the 1985 overthrow of 
longtime dictator gaafar nimeiri 
alkhartoum said parties from wartorn southern sudan would draw 
four portfolios and independent parties and national parties from 
western sudan would get one each 
the national islamic front will not be in the cabinet the 
newspaper said the front has rejected the pact signed 10 days ago 
by the other parties 
the plan calls for immediate endorsement of a peace proposal 
reached last november by the rebels and the democratic unionists 
