<DOCNO> AP890312-0017 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
since alan b shepard made his 
15minute suborbital flight aboard the mercury capsule freedom 7 in 
1961 counting down the final seconds to launch has been a mans job 
on monday lisa malone changes all that 
the 27yearold public affairs specialist with nasa at the 
kennedy space center will replace hugh harris as the voice of 
shuttle launch control for the liftoff of discovery it will be the 
first time a woman has served as launch commentator for a flight 
carrying astronauts 
her job will be to guide the news media and the public through 
the anxious minutes before the main engines ignite in a burst of 
flame and smoke until the shuttle clears the launch tower and 
communications switch to the johnson space center in houston 
her challenge to explain what is taking place behind the scenes 
and to translate the technical chatter among launch managers into 
something that anybody can understand 
malone is quick to contrast the significance of her new role with 
that of female astronauts 
i think what theyre doing is a lot more trendsetting and 
important than what a commentator does she said because 
theyre actually doing it instead of reporting on whats been done 
nevertheless malone said she likes to think her voice will be 
an inspiration to young women 
if that would inspire somebody to go on and achieve what they 
want in life she says i think that is fantastic 
malone has worked for nasa for seven years rising to her 
position of space shuttle specialist from a college workstudy 
program that started while she was earning a bachelors degree in 
journalism from the university of alabama in tuscaloosa 
she edited the space center newsletter spaceport news for three 
years before she was assigned to the space shuttle beat now she 
attends several daily meetings of launch managers to stay uptodate 
on the progress of work to get three orbiters and their external 
fuel tanks and booster rockets ready for flight 
to prepare for her debut malone provided launch commentary for 
some unmanned atlas centaur and delta launches and for the early 
portions of some shuttle countdowns she has watched numerous 
launches from her seat at the firing room console beside harris who 
is now deputy director for public affairs at kennedy space center 
she also hired a voice coach 
although she has learned the lingo and has carefully prepared a 
script malone knows her biggest challenge will be the realtime 
element of the job and how shell react if theres an unexpected 
problem during the countdown 
youre going to be scrambling to try and figure out what it is 
because you want to have the right story before you tell the world 
whats going on malone said 
