a ninemember congressional commission recently 
recommended a 50 percent pay raises for judges government officials 
and lawmakers nobody got a penny of it 
a 14member commission created by congress labored for a year on 
ways to reduce the federal deficit it ended hopelessly deadlocked 
now an eightmember commission appointed by president bush to 
come up with ethical standards applying equally to all three 
branches of government has reported that it cant be done 
the ethics panel report released friday is one more bit of 
evidence that sometimes the commissions government creates to help 
with its problems produce more rhetoric than results 
as a mayor or a governor or a president or a legislative body 
that is being criticized for something looks for something to do 
one of the easiest things to do is to study the matter to create a 
commission said donald rumsfeld a former secretary of defense 
and a member of the deficit reduction panel 
some serve a useful purpose some dont he added 
as rumsfeld noted washington has no monopoly on the idea of a 
study panel 
joe pisciotte a professor of government at wichita state 
university in kansas studied commissions created by the city of 
wichita 
the term i would use for some of them is the politics of 
avoidance that if the governing body doesnt want to deal with a 
particularly sensitive problem itself it will create a board or 
commission or task force and pass the heat so to speak pisciotte 
said 
although pisciotte studied the phenomenon in his own back yard 
he thinks his conclusions also would apply to many federal 
commissions 
i think the pay commission was a prime example that was too 
politically sensitive too politically difficult so the people 
who were ultimately responsible for that passed the heat he said 
as to why some commissions produce more results than others 
experts say there is no single answer 
one of the most successful commissions in recent years was the 
15member national commission on social security reform created by 
president reagan in 1981 which prepared the blueprint for a social 
security rescue bill that barreled through congress in a matter of 
weeks 
