<TEXT>
everglades game fish are suddenly showing mercury 
levels among the highest ever recorded in the united states 
alarming experts who are searching for a cause 
last week floridas department of health and rehabilitative 
services issued health warnings against eating largemouth bass and 
warmouth caught in western parts of palm beach broward and dade 
counties 
fish samples contained up to 44 parts per million more than 
four times the amount of methyl mercury that the federal government 
considers safe 
the everglades mercury is attracting attention because the 
precious environment there is already reeling 
thats one of the highest concentrations ever recorded in the 
country said frank ditri a michigan state university expert on 
mercury to find concentration up to 5 or 6 parts per million in 
fish he said he had to go back to 1970 and that was in a lake 
contaminated by hundreds of pounds of mercury from a factory 
new tests have been ordered all over southeastern florida in the 
wake of the unexpected findings 
scientists are puzzled by the discovery of methyl mercury in the 
everglades while the poisonous metal has been found frequently in 
the heavily industrialized northeast it hasnt been found much in 
floridas rural swampland 
mercury which is especially dangerous to an unborn fetus can 
cause central nervous system damage that leads to deafness 
numbness reduced vision loss of coordination and trembling eating 
enough everglades fish to cause such damage would take months but 
over a long enough time poisoning would show its effects 
there are many theories on how the metal entered the environment 
according to scientists 
winds from other regions could have blown mercuryladen factory 
smoke from as far away as mexico into southern florida or midnight 
dumpers could have thrown residue from some electronic manufacturer 
secretly into the everglades another theory holds that fire 
drought and rain could combine to leech the heavy metal from 
naturally occurring deposits in the soil 
some scientists lean toward a theory that the contaminant has 
lain in the muck at the bottom of the everglades since before 
mercury was banned from pesticides two decades ago 
this may have been something that has been down here for 20 
years or so said university of miami epidemiologist dr thomas 
briggle it has been that long since there was a legal fungicide 
using mercury 
the likely sources would have been the sugarcane fields that dot 
the area 
briggle speculates that the recent drought and water shortages 
have forced the water district to move water around inside the 
everglades disturbing the mercuryladen muck at the bottom of 
canals 
once the mercury was back in the water it entered the food chain 
and was concentrated in the bass and warmouth predators at the top 
burkett neely director of the loxahatchee national wildlife 
refuge has doubts about the old fungicide theory however he notes 
the pattern of the findings none have been found north of the 
agricultural areas in lake okeechobee suggest the contamination 
began more recently at a specific point or points 
in addition while the drought is serious other years have been 
as bad yet as recently as three years ago fish samples showed far 
lower mercury levels 
we had some kind of event in the last three years that has put 
a lot of mercury into the system neely said something happened 
at the north end of the everglades and traveled south 
contamination from agriculture is one possibility another he 
said is the illegal dumping by someone using nearby us highway 
27 theres no telling whats in those canals neely said 
although the fish show no ill effects and people have now been 
warned against eating them there still may be victims said dan 
dunford director of the everglades office of the florida game and 
fresh water fish commission 
several animals including otters raccoons and such endangered 
species as everglades mink wood storks and snail kites could be at 
risk from mercury in the fish they eat or in other prey 
</TEXT>
