cafeterias at the nations secondlargest 
school district will stop serving apples to students this week in 
response to a report finding a cancer risk to children from a 
chemical residue on some fruit 
the ban also includes any apple products including juice pies 
and applesauce said los angeles unified school district officials 
the districts 592000 students have eaten more than 5 million 
apples each year second only to the new york city school system 
where students consumed 13 million apples new york schools enacted 
a similar ban last week 
thats a lot of apples so we decided to do it in order to 
protect the health and safety of students said los angeles 
district spokeswoman eva hain 
the bans in los angeles and new york followed a feb 28 report by 
the washingtonbased national resources defense council which said 
the chemical daminozide could increase the incidence of cancer in 
children 
daminozide sold under the brand name alar is sprayed on apple 
trees in the spring and acts to keep apples on the tree longer that 
makes harvesting easier improves the apples color and firmness 
and extends their shelf life 
alar permeates the fruits skin and cannot be peeled off or 
washed away 
apple growers have criticized the report contending that only 4 
percent of the apples sold in the united states show any traces of 
alar and that those traces fall well below federal environmental 
protection agency levels 
