<DOCNO> AP890312-0072 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
israeli researchers have found a link between 
sex hormones and the skeletal system of animals opening the way to 
a better understanding of osteoporosis the weizmann institute of 
science said sunday 
the findings could help explain the high incidence of the 
degenerative bone disease in women following menopause a statement 
from the institute said 
the institute discovered in recent experiments with laboratory 
rats that the skeletal system responds to the animals main sex 
hormone the institutes statement said 
osteoporosis is characterized by increased porousness and 
brittleness in bones associated with the loss of calcium it leads 
to an increased risk of fracture 
an estimated 15 to 20 million people suffer from the disease in 
the united states alone resulting in an annual total of 13 million 
fractures with a mortality rate of 5 to 14 percent according to 
figures from the institute there is no known cure only methods of 
slowing the progress of the disease 
although sex hormone deficiency has been associated with 
osteoporosis and such hormones have been used for treatment the 
disease was believed to result from processes only indirectly 
related to hormone deficiency said institute spokesman nehemiah 
myers 
the research team was led by professor alvin m kaye of the 
institutes hormone research and included his associates from tel 
aviv university 
the study is to be published in the proceedings of the national 
academy of sciences of the united states 
the research shows that bones of female rats respond biologically 
to the female hormone estrogen but are unaffected by its male 
counterpart testosterone in male rats bone tissue is stimulated 
selectively by testosterone 
but kaye added the situation in bones is quite complex and 
the stimulatory effects of estrogen and testosterone here are 
closely linked to other factors including the level of vitamin d 
metabolites 
the interdependence of these reactions could help explain why 
there has never been a clear association between the level of blood 
estrogen and the appearance of osteoporosis kaye said 
osteoporosis is much more prevalent in women who may undergo an 
80 percent reduction in estrogen production following menopause the 
institute said it noted that men show only a moderate lowering of 
testosterone levels 
kaye is a professor of endocrinology at the institute which is a 
leading israeli research facility in the natural sciences it is in 
rehovot south of tel aviv 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

